event.descr: A polling-style trap built using the 'snmp traps' command on the filer.
Disk Health Monitor - Reported a Disk Degraded-I/O Event
Disk Health Monitor - Reported a Disk Predictive-Failure Event
A user-defined trap indicating an extremely urgent situation, usually indicating that the system has failed and is shutting down.
A user-defined trap indicating a condition that should be corrected immediately, such as a failed disk.
A user-defined trap indicating a critical condition, such as a hard device error.
A user-defined trap indicating an error condition, such as a mistake in a configuration file.
A user-defined trap indicating a condition which is not an error, but which may require special handling.
A user-defined trap meant to provide notification, such as an hourly uptime message.
A user-defined trap used for informational purposes.

A user-defined trap used for debugging purposes. This trap was previously mis-documented as being trap number 17, with the name debugTrap. It has always, actually, been trap 18. The name change is to avoid issues with environments that already have a record for debugTrap.
System is shutting down because the system has been running in degraded mode for 24 hours. The trap includes a string describing the failed disk.
One or more disks failed. The trap includes a string describing the failed disk(s).
The failed disks have been repaired. This trap is a placeholder - it is not currently sent by ONTAP.
Critical chassis or cpu fans have failed and the system is shutting down.
One or more chassis fans failed. The trap includes a string describing the failed fan(s).
One or more chassis or cpu fans are in warning state. The trap includes a string describing the fan(s) in the warning state.
All fans are repaired.
Critical power supplies or power rails failed and the system is shutting down.
One or more redundant power supplies failed. Include in the trap a string describing the failed power supply(ies).
One or more power supplies or power rails in warning state. Include in the trap a string describing the power supply(ies) or the power rail(s) in the warning state.
Previously-failed power supplies or power rails have been repaired.

CPU utilization exceeds 90%. This trap is not enabled by default. To enable this trap set the registry entry options.monitor.cpu.enable to on. Note that as the threshold for this trap is checked once a minute it is possible to receive multiple instances of this trap in a short time.
CPU utilization has dropped back below 90%. This trap is a placeholder - it is not currently sent by ONTAP.
The NVRAM battery is fully discharged.
The charge in the NVRAM battery is low.
A node in a Cluster FailOver configuration failed. Its partner will assume service for the failed node.
The partner has taken over for a failed cluster node.
A cluster node has resumed operation.
At least one volume is more than 98% full. Volume or volumes which exceed the threshold: %parm[#1]%
At least one volume is more than 95% full. Volume or volumes which exceed the threshold: %parm[#1]%
All volumes are now under 95% full.
System temperature is too high to continue operating. The system is shutting down.
System temperature is too high and in the warning level.
System temperature has returned to an acceptable value.
A disk storage shelf reported a fault, probably due to a problem with drive placement, fans, power, or temperature.
A previously-reported shelf fault is now corrected.
The appliance's overall status changed to 'nonRecoverable', indicating a problem so severe that the appliance is shutting down.
The appliance's overall status changed to 'critical', indicating a problem that needs immediate attention.
The appliance's overall status changed to 'nonCritical', indicating a problem that needs attention.
The appliance's overall status returned to normal.
A user has exceeded their soft quota limit.
A user is safely back under their soft quota limit.
Unable to send autosupport. The trap includes a string describing the reason for the failure.
Autosupport may be configured incorrectly. The trap includes a string describing the mis-configuration.
Autosupport was sent successfully.
UPS: Input line power has failed and UPS is now on battery.
UPS: Battery exhausted, system is shutting down.
UPS: Warning: Time left on battery is getting critical.
UPS: Input line power has been restored and UPS is now off battery.
The application encountered an extremely urgent situation and requires an immediate response.
The application is in a condition that should be corrected immediately.
The application encountered a critical condition.
The application encountered an error condition.
The application is in a condition which is not an error, but which may require special handling.
The application is notifing of a certain event.
The application's message is meant for informational purposes.
The application requires to be debugged.
The internal audit file has wrapped. You are currently losing event records.Warning the user
The internal audit log has been autosaved to an external evt file. Notifying the user.
The internal audit log file is nearly full. The file is going to wrap. Notifying the user

One of the quota limits has been exceeded. The trap includes a string describing the specific event which triggered the trap. The string is structured in the following form: Quota Event: status=exceeded, type={hard|soft|threshold}, user={username}, volume={volume}, limit_item={files|disk}, limit_value={#files|#kilobytes} [ , treeid={tree-id} ] [ , vfiler={vfiler} ] An example of a complete message would be: Quota Event: status=exceeded, type=soft, user=admin, volume=vol1, limit_item=disk, limit_value=1000000, treeid=8 Additional key=value items may, in the future, be appended to this message.

One of the quota limits has gone back down to a normal level. The trap includes a string describing the specific event which triggered the trap. The string is structured in the following form: Quota Event: status=normal, type={hard|soft|threshold}, user={username}, volume={volume}, limit_item={files|disk}, limit_value={#files|#kilobytes} [ , treeid={tree-id} ] [ , vfiler={vfiler} ] An example of a complete message would be: Quota Event: status=normal, type=soft, user=admin, volume=vol1, limit_item=disk, limit_value=1000000, treeid=8 Additional key=value items may, in the future, be appended to this message.
The directory has been filled to its limit
Memory ECC: number of new correctable ECC errors
Memory ECC: High frequency of ECC errors
Ftp daemon: service stopped
Ftp daemon: number of connections hits maximum number
Ftp daemon: number of connections nearly hits maximum number
SCSI Target: FCP Partner Path Misconfigured
SCSI Target: Throttle limit event notification
Vif: The primary Interface on a Single mode vif has failed
Vif: All the links of the vif have failed
A vFiler has stopped.
A vFiler has started.
VScan: Vscan scanner has detected a virus on the Filer
VScan: There has been a connection to the vscan servers dropped
VScan: There has been a change to the vscan configuration
VScan: The Vscan server has been upgraded

A volume that experienced a medium error during reconstruction is restricted and marked wafl-inconsistent, but starting wafliron has failed. This trap is issued to alert operator that a volume is not accessible and wafliron must be started to allow access to it.
This trap is issued when we unmount a volume due to an inconsistency.
Volume is being taken offline or being restricted. The string sent with trap specifies name of affected volume and its state.
Volume is online now. The string sent with trap specifies name of volume which is online now.
Remote Management Controller card needs replacement. The trap includes a string specifying the reason for replacement
Remote Management Controller card is missing its internal cable, or LAN cable or power supply cable. The trap includes a string specifing the missing component.
Volume is restricted due to a root volume conflict. The string sent with trap specifies name of conflicting volume which is being restricted.
Volume can not be brought online because its raw size is larger than maximum allowed size. The string sent with trap specifies name of affected volume and its raw size, and maximum allowed size.
Volume is being taken offline. The string sent with trap specifies name of affected volume and reason for being taken offline.
Volume is being restricted. The string sent with trap specifies name of affected volume and reason for being restricted.
Volume is degraded and has dirty parity. WAFL_check must be run on this volume before it can be brought online. The string sent with trap specifies name of affected volume.
This trap is issued when a volume can not be brought online due to an error. The string sent with trap specifies name of affected volume and error description.
Synchronous SnapMirror failed and went into asynchronous mode.
Synchronous SnapMirror went into synchronous mode.
